<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900507-0128</DOCNO><DOCID>900507-0128.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Navy Aide Pleads Guilty   In Pentagon Bribery Case</HL><DATE>05/07/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   LIT UTX</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Former Navy acquisition official GeorgeStone pleaded guilty to conspiracy and another chargestemming from the nationwide investigation of Pentagonbribery and influence-peddling.   Mr. Stone, who supervised Marine Corps contracts as amid-level civilian official through the late 1980s, wasindicted on broader charges two months ago for helpingsubsidiaries of Litton Industries Inc. and UnitedTechnologies Corp. obtain bid-related information. The twocompanies haven't been accused of any wrongdoing, but twodefense-industry consultants and three former executives ofUnited Technologies' Norden Systems subsidiary have beenconvicted of conspiring to attempt to illegally secure some$150 million of Marine Corps business.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Stone initially fought the charges against him. ButFriday in Alexandria, Va., federal district court, he agreedto cooperate with the continuing grand jury inquiry andpleaded guilty to two felony counts. He could face a total of15 years in jail and a $500,000 fine.   In documents filed with the guilty plea, prosecutors forthe first time provided details about how Mr. Stonepersonally intervened to keep Norden in the competition for aMarine Corps radar-and-communications contract in 1988.</TEXT></DOC>